      <td class="loser">Inefficient mess</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Method 3: Car Inverter + AC Charger (Don't Do This)</h3>

<p>Some people buy a car inverter, plug the power station's AC wall charger into it, and charge that way.</p>

<p>This works. But it's stupid.</p>

<p>You're converting DC (car battery) → AC (inverter) → DC (power station). Two conversions. Each wastes 10–15% as heat. You lose 20–30% of your energy to inefficiency. The inverter gets hot. The charger gets hot. Your car outlet might trip.</p>

<p>Just use the DC cable directly. Skip the double conversion. It's faster, safer, and doesn't involve a $40 inverter heating up behind your seat.</p>

<div class="warning-box">
  <div class="warning-title">⚠️ Don't Use Method 3</div>
  <p>I'm listing it because people ask about it. I tested it once. The car inverter hit 160°F. The AC charger was too hot to touch. Combined efficiency was about 68%. I unplugged everything, said a word Sarah disapproves of, and went back to the DC cable.</p>
</div>

<div class="section-divider">• • •</div>

<h2>The Road Trip Test — Real Results</h2>

<p>Denver to Moab. 350 miles. 6 hours including one gas stop. September, 78°F outside. 2021 Toyota 4Runner. All four stations started at 0%.</p>

<p>I tested two on the cigarette lighter (one at a time, swapped halfway) and two on direct-to-battery cables.</p>

