<h3>The Emergency Scenario</h3>

<p>This one deserves extra attention. Power goes out at home. You have a power station running the fridge and CPAP. After 10 hours, the battery is getting low. No sun for solar. What do you do?</p>

<p>You go outside. Start your car. Connect the power station. Let the engine idle for 2–3 hours. The alternator charges the station. Turn off the car. Bring the station back inside.</p>

<p>A gallon of gas running your car at idle for 2 hours charges about 400–600Wh via direct-to-battery. That's another 8–10 hours of fridge runtime. Three dollars in gas for a night of food preservation.</p>

<p>This is how people survived multi-day outages during Hurricane Milton. Car as generator. Power station as battery. Rotate as needed.</p>

<div class="highlight-box">
  <strong>Emergency car charging protocol:</strong><br><br>
  1. Park in driveway, windows down for ventilation if in garage (NEVER idle in a closed garage)<br>
  2. Connect direct-to-battery cable to power station<br>
  3. Start engine, let idle<br>
  4. Charge for 2–3 hours (~400–600Wh gained)<br>
  5. Disconnect station, turn off engine<br>
  6. Bring station inside, reconnect fridge/CPAP/essentials<br>
  7. Repeat once daily as needed<br><br>
  One tank of gas (15 gallons) = roughly 7–10 charging sessions = <strong>a week or more of essential power</strong>.
</div>

