<h2>What About Electric Cars and Hybrids?</h2>

<p>Great question. Different answer.</p>

<h3>Hybrids (Toyota RAV4 Hybrid, Ford Maverick, etc.)</h3>

<p>Hybrids are actually <em>better</em> for this than regular cars. Their engines are already designed to run efficiently at idle to charge the hybrid battery. Many hybrids have larger 12V outlets or even built-in 120V AC outlets in the bed (Ford Maverick, Toyota Tundra i-Force Max).</p>

<p>The Ford Maverick's Pro Power Onboard outlet puts out 2,400W. You could plug in your power station's AC wall charger and fill a 1,000Wh station in about an hour. While using a gallon of gas. That's wildly efficient.</p>

<h3>PHEVs (Plug-in Hybrids)</h3>

<p>Even better. A Mitsubishi Outlander PHEV or Toyota RAV4 Prime can run on electric-only mode, meaning your alternator works without burning gas at all — at least until the hybrid battery depletes. You could charge your power station for free from a charged PHEV.</p>

<h3>Full Electric (Tesla, Rivian, etc.)</h3>

<p>Complicated. Most EVs don't have a traditional 12V outlet capable of high-power output. Some have 120V outlets (Rivian R1T has four). You can charge a power station from those, but you're essentially transferring energy from a big battery (your car) to a small battery (your power station). It works, but feels like pouring water between buckets.</p>

<p>The real play with an EV: just use the car's outlets directly to power your devices. A Rivian R1T with a full battery has 135,000Wh. That's 135 power stations. You don't need a middleman.</p>

