<h2>FAQ — Quick Answers</h2>

<h3>Can I charge while the car is parked with the engine off?</h3>
<p>Technically yes. But you'll drain your car battery. A power station pulling 100W from a 50Ah car battery will kill it in about 4–5 hours. If you can't start your car, your power station problem becomes a much bigger problem. Always run the engine while charging.</p>

<h3>Will this void my car's warranty?</h3>
<p>Using the cigarette lighter: no. Direct-to-battery with proper fusing: extremely unlikely, but check your manual. I've never heard of a warranty claim denied for this. The alternator doesn't care what it's charging.</p>

<h3>Can I charge two power stations from one car?</h3>
<p>One on the cigarette lighter, one on direct-to-battery? Yes. Different circuits, different connections. I've done it. Total draw was about 520W. The 4Runner's alternator didn't flinch. Voltage dipped from 14.1V to 13.6V. Still well within safe range.</p>

<h3>What about a motorcycle or ATV?</h3>
<p>Smaller alternators. A motorcycle alternator typically produces 200–400W. Charging a power station at 100W is fine. At 400W, you'll strain the system. Stick with the cigarette lighter cable on small vehicles and charge small stations (under 500Wh).</p>

<h3>Does temperature affect car charging speed?</h3>
<p>Yes. In extreme cold (below 32°F), LiFePO4 batteries slow their charge rate to protect themselves. You might see 60–70% of normal charging speed. Li-ion batteries are less affected but still slow slightly. In summer heat, no issues — if anything, the station charges slightly faster.</p>

